column3: The Third Wave developed over such a short period of time because Ron Jones, a history teacher at Cubberley High School, conducted an experiment on his students to teach them about German mentality. Jones established rules in his classroom and developed an authoritative dictatorship to enforce his students to behave in a more orderly way. As once student began changing their actions and behaviors, all other students quickly joined.  When the fourth day of the experiment came along, Jones felt as if he was loosing control of his students. This was because their involvement in the experiment was increasing and their loyalty, as well as discipline was becoming too much. As a result, Jones decided it was best if he just terminated the entire experiment.
column4: The Third Wave emerged unexpectedly and quickly due to Ron Jones's experimental approach in the classroom. Jones established rules and implemented an authoritative dictatorship to ensure orderly behavior among his students. As one student's actions changed, the rest of the students gradually followed suit. However, as Jones's control over his students grew, he began to lose the reins of their behavior. Consequently, he terminated the experiment after four days, fearing that the students' involvement was becoming overwhelming and could potentially lead to rebellion.
